PROFILE_ROW = {'id': 'profile-alex-van-poppel', 'first_name': 'Alex', 'last_name': 'van Poppel', 'headline': 'a software engineering and AI student', 'short_intro': 'I am a Software Development student at Thomas More in Geel who enjoys building applications that are useful in practice, from full-stack web platforms to AI experiments and the infrastructure needed to host them.', 'long_bio': "Hi, I'm Alex van Poppel, a Software Development student at Thomas More in Geel. I chose Applied Computer Science because I have always been curious about how technology works behind the screen, not just how to use an app, but how the systems underneath actually run. That curiosity is what pulled me toward software engineering, AI, and the more technical side of infrastructure.\n\nMost of the work I enjoy sits somewhere between building and understanding. I like creating web applications, thinking through data structures, and turning rough requirements into something people can actually use. At the same time, I enjoy learning what happens around the application itself: deployment, networking, storage, and how to keep a system maintainable once it leaves the classroom.\n\nOutside of school, I spend a lot of time solving small real-world problems for myself through scripts and personal tools, experimenting with my NAS and homelab, and building or upgrading PCs. Those hobbies have made me more practical as a developer, because they keep pulling me back to the same question: how do I make this work well, and keep it working well later?", 'location': 'Lommel, Belgium', 'email': 'alexanderlommel@gmail.com', 'phone': '+32 472 31 34 79', 'avatar_file_id': 'file-avatar-alex', 'hero_image_file_id': 'file-hero-portrait', 'resume_file_id': 'file-resume', 'cta_primary_label': 'Download Resume', 'cta_primary_url': 'media://resume', 'cta_secondary_label': 'Contact me', 'cta_secondary_url': '/contact', 'is_public': True, 'created_at': '2026-04-17T10:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2026-04-17T10:00:00Z'}

PROJECT_ROWS = [{'id': 'project-internal-exchange-student-portal', 'slug': 'internal-exchange-student-portal', 'title': 'Internal Exchange Student Portal', 'teaser': 'A student portal for managing international exchanges and guiding students through the academic process abroad.', 'summary': 'This client-facing school project focused on building a clear, user-friendly platform for international exchange students. Our team first reviewed the work of three other teams, combined their strongest ideas into a single prototype, and then developed the approved solution iteratively using Scrum.', 'description_markdown': '## Project overview\n\nThis project was built to support international exchange students throughout their study journey. The goal was to create a platform that could make the process less confusing by centralising guidance, resources, and communication in one place.\n\n## My role\n\nI took the lead during the analysis phase. My team reviewed the solution documents created by three other teams, identified the strongest ideas in each one, and combined them into a single prototype that we later presented to the client. Once the concept was approved, I worked heavily on the frontend and on shaping the underlying data structure of the application. I also stayed in regular contact with the product owner so we could validate features early and keep the platform easy to use.\n\n## Stack and workflow\n\n- Laravel and Livewire for the application\n- Tailwind CSS for styling\n- Figma for prototyping and review\n- Git and GitHub for collaboration\n- Scrum for planning and iterative delivery\n\n## Challenges\n\nOne of the biggest challenges was combining different design ideas and technical approaches into one coherent direction. We solved that by discussing trade-offs openly, justifying each feature, and keeping the client close to the process. That helped reduce confusion later and gave the final platform a clearer identity.\n\n## Outcome\n\nBy the end of the project, we had a complete portal that could support students from enrolment and planning through to the wider exchange process. More importantly, it taught me a lot about leadership, analysis, and how much smoother development becomes when the prototype phase is handled well.', 'cover_image_file_id': 'file-project-exchange-cover', 'cover_image_alt': 'Exchange student portal interface preview', 'github_url': None, 'github_repo_name': None, 'demo_url': 'https://www.alex-vp.com', 'company_name': 'Thomas More client project', 'started_on': '2025-02-01', 'ended_on': '2025-06-30', 'duration_label': '5 months', 'status': 'Completed', 'state': 'completed', 'is_featured': False, 'sort_order': 1, 'published_at': '2025-07-05T09:00:00Z', 'created_at': '2025-07-05T09:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2025-07-05T09:00:00Z'}, {'id': 'project-iot-security-system', 'slug': 'iot-security-system', 'title': 'IoT Security System', 'teaser': 'A playful security prototype that combined computer vision, embedded control, and custom 3D-printed hardware.', 'summary': 'For this IoT project, my team built a hardware-software demo that detects a person, aims a water gun at them, and triggers a smoke-screen effect when they get too close. It was a fun concept, but also a serious exercise in system integration, timing, and hardware limitations.', 'description_markdown': "## Concept\n\nThis project brought together AI, electronics, and mechanical design in one system. A camera feed was used to detect a person's head, stepper motors aimed the turret, and a water gun handled the final action. If someone moved too close, a relay-controlled fog machine added a second defensive effect.\n\n## My contribution\n\nI was responsible for the 3D modelling side of the project, including the design and printing of the mounts for the water gun, camera, and motors. I also contributed to the control logic that connected the detection step to motor movement, helping translate visual input into a stable mechanical response.\n\n## Stack\n\n- Python and OpenCV for the detection pipeline\n- Orange Pi as the main controller\n- Stepper motors for movement\n- Relay-controlled smoke output\n- FreeCAD and 3D printing for the custom housing\n\n## Challenges\n\nThe main technical challenge was keeping the system responsive without making the turret shake or overshoot. We improved this by adding cooldown logic and by tuning the sensitivity of the detection step. We also had to work around the limits of the Orange Pi, which meant simplifying parts of the onboard AI pipeline so the system remained usable in real time.\n\n## Reflection\n\nThis project taught me a lot about the gap between a cool idea and a working system. It also made me much more confident in combining software with physical design, especially when there are real-world constraints like hardware performance, motion control, and mounting stability.", 'cover_image_file_id': 'file-project-iot-cover', 'cover_image_alt': 'IoT turret and water gun security system flyer', 'github_url': None, 'github_repo_name': None, 'demo_url': None, 'company_name': 'Thomas More', 'started_on': '2024-05-01', 'ended_on': '2024-07-31', 'duration_label': '3 months', 'status': 'Completed', 'state': 'completed', 'is_featured': True, 'sort_order': 2, 'published_at': '2024-08-10T09:00:00Z', 'created_at': '2024-08-10T09:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2024-08-10T09:00:00Z'}, {'id': 'project-laravel-portfolio-website', 'slug': 'laravel-portfolio-website', 'title': 'Old Laravel Portfolio', 'teaser': 'My earlier self-hosted portfolio, built to present projects, skills, and achievements in a dynamic way.', 'summary': 'This was my previous portfolio website, built with the TALL stack so I could present my work more dynamically. It gave me a full end-to-end project of my own, from data modelling and UI work to hosting it on infrastructure I managed myself.', 'description_markdown': '## Why I built it\n\nI wanted a portfolio that did more than show static text. The site was designed to present my projects, skills, and course work clearly while also giving me a chance to practise building and hosting something of my own.\n\n## Stack\n\n- Laravel\n- Livewire\n- Tailwind CSS\n- Alpine.js\n- SQLite\n\n## What I handled\n\nThis was a solo project, so I was responsible for the full process: design ideas, data modelling, migrations, seeders, backend logic, reusable Blade components, filtering behaviour, styling, and deployment.\n\n## Deployment and hosting\n\nOne of the most valuable parts of this project was hosting it myself. I routed traffic through my own setup using Cloudflare, Nginx, Docker, and a TrueNAS-based server environment. That made the portfolio feel much closer to a real deployment than a project that only ever runs locally.\n\n## Reflection\n\nBuilding this portfolio taught me a lot about modular design, self-hosting, and how quickly content can become hard to manage if it lives too close to the code. That lesson is also what pushed me toward rebuilding my portfolio later with a cleaner content workflow.', 'cover_image_file_id': 'file-project-laravel-portfolio-cover', 'cover_image_alt': 'Older Laravel portfolio homepage preview', 'github_url': None, 'github_repo_name': None, 'demo_url': 'https://www.alex-vp.com', 'company_name': 'Personal project', 'started_on': '2025-03-01', 'ended_on': '2025-04-30', 'duration_label': '2 months', 'status': 'Completed', 'state': 'completed', 'is_featured': False, 'sort_order': 3, 'published_at': '2025-05-05T09:00:00Z', 'created_at': '2025-05-05T09:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2025-05-05T09:00:00Z'}]

PROJECT_SKILL_NAMES_BY_PROJECT_SLUG = {'internal-exchange-student-portal': ['Laravel', 'Tailwind CSS', 'Git', 'Requirements Analysis', 'Prototyping', 'Team Leadership'], 'iot-security-system': ['Python', 'Machine Learning', 'Git', 'Prototyping'], 'laravel-portfolio-website': ['Laravel', 'Tailwind CSS', 'Git', 'Docker', 'Networking Basics', 'SQL']}

BLOG_POST_ROWS = [{'id': 'blog-my-homelab', 'slug': 'my-homelab', 'title': 'My Homelab', 'excerpt': 'A look at the homelab setup I use to learn more about storage, hosting, networking, and running my own tools.', 'content_markdown': '## My Homelab\n\nHomelabbing started out as curiosity for me. I wanted to understand more than just the applications I was building, so I slowly began experimenting with the systems behind them: storage, routing, virtualisation, and self-hosting. What began as a small personal setup turned into one of the most practical ways I have learned outside of class.\n\n## What I am running\n\nAt the centre of my setup is a NAS and homelab environment that I use to host personal tools, test deployments, and learn how infrastructure fits around software. I regularly experiment with things like Proxmox, TrueNAS, Docker, reverse proxies, and networking basics.\n\nSome parts of the lab are there for convenience, like hosting services I want to use privately. Other parts exist purely so I can learn by doing. That mix keeps it fun, because I am not just spinning up containers for the sake of it. I am usually solving a real small problem for myself at the same time.\n\n## Why it matters to me\n\nWorking on a homelab has made me a much more practical developer. It forced me to think about topics that are easy to ignore when a project only runs on localhost: backups, uptime, storage, networking, deployment, and how to recover when something breaks.\n\nThat has changed the way I approach software projects too. I now think a lot more about what happens after the code works for the first time. Can I deploy it cleanly? Can I update it safely? Will it still make sense in a few months?\n\n## What I want to explore next\n\nRight now, I mainly use the lab to keep improving my understanding of infrastructure and self-hosting. In the future, I want to go deeper into automation, monitoring, and more structured container orchestration so the environment becomes not just useful, but also easier to maintain.\n\nFor me, that is the best part of homelabbing: there is always another layer to understand.', 'cover_image_file_id': 'file-blog-homelab-cover', 'cover_image_alt': "Diagram of Alex van Poppel's homelab setup", 'reading_time_minutes': 5, 'status': 'published', 'is_featured': True, 'published_at': '2026-04-10T09:00:00Z', 'seo_title': 'My Homelab | Alex van Poppel', 'seo_description': 'A casual walkthrough of the homelab setup I use to learn self-hosting, storage, networking, and deployment.', 'created_at': '2026-04-10T09:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2026-04-10T09:00:00Z'}, {'id': 'blog-mobilab-internship', 'slug': 'mobilab-internship', 'title': 'MobiLab Internship', 'excerpt': 'A short reflection on building a medical assistant inference system during my internship and what it taught me about AI in practice.', 'content_markdown': '## MobiLab Internship\n\nDuring my internship, I worked on a medical assistant inference system designed to support treatment suggestions. It was the kind of project that immediately caught my attention because it sat right at the intersection of software engineering, AI, and real-world usefulness.\n\n## What I worked on\n\nThe system was built around an inference workflow that could process medical context and return structured guidance. My work focused on helping shape and implement the application side of that system, with attention to how the components fit together and how the solution could be deployed in a clean, maintainable way.\n\nThe project also gave me exposure to the infrastructure side of modern AI systems. Instead of treating the model as an isolated piece, I had to think about containers, service boundaries, and how inference could be made reliable in a broader platform.\n\n## Why it was valuable\n\nOne thing I appreciated during this internship was seeing how different AI work feels when it moves beyond a notebook or school assignment. In a more realistic setting, the challenge is not just whether something can produce an answer, but whether it can be structured, integrated, and maintained well enough to be useful.\n\nThat was a great learning experience for me, because it connected a lot of interests I already had: Python, AI, APIs, and deployment. It also made me more interested in the architecture around intelligent systems, not just the model itself.\n\n## Takeaway\n\nThe internship gave me a clearer picture of the kind of work I enjoy most: technical enough to be challenging, practical enough to matter, and broad enough that I can think about both the application and the system around it. It is exactly the kind of experience that made me want to keep exploring applied AI and backend engineering further.', 'cover_image_file_id': 'file-blog-mobilab-cover', 'cover_image_alt': 'Container diagram from the MobiLab internship project', 'reading_time_minutes': 4, 'status': 'published', 'is_featured': False, 'published_at': '2026-04-14T09:00:00Z', 'seo_title': 'MobiLab Internship | Alex van Poppel', 'seo_description': 'Reflections on working on a medical assistant AI inference system during an internship.', 'created_at': '2026-04-14T09:00:00Z', 'updated_at': '2026-04-14T09:00:00Z'}]

BLOG_TAG_NAMES_BY_POST_SLUG = {'my-homelab': ['Homelabbing', 'TrueNAS', 'Proxmox', 'Networking'], 'mobilab-internship': ['Kubernetes', 'AI', 'Python']}
